{"author":{"id":"02ecfeec5e3d9ae3fcb4ee7636634148fee4f97bfc8cfa132041bf8882dd22ae"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1491392446,"nonce":"3kUWWSPWqxCh16ReB0LSP1EBwA8=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDI5MTgzNTA4OQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/1230#issuecomment-291835089"},"message":"I think that the label \"best practice\" has become incorrectly used with regard to the tools-iuc repository - it should refer only to the way the tool is written (i.e., the code).  But it has somehow evolved into encompassing the functional correctness of the tool's execution, (i.e., only those tools that are labeled \"best practice\" will be functionally correct).\n\nI also feel that the \"best practice\" rules that pertain to the tools-iuc repository are not clear, not documented and too restrictive in that they require code that is more complex to write and maintain, seemingly in order to save on the number of lines.  I fully agree that the number of lines of code is important, and the fewer the better.  However, in many cases the tools-iuc rule of having to write tools in bash results in code that requires both an expert programmer to write it and an expert programmer to maintain it over time.  This significantly restricts the pool of tool maintainers that can participate in the tools-iuc repository.\n\nMy opinion is that the tools-iuc \"best practices\" should be more balanced, and that the functional correctness of the tool should be a higher priority for acceptance into the tools-iuc repository.\n\nTools should include tests, which implies that the \"test framework\" (which may include items like Planemo or Galaxy itself) must accommodate standard Galaxy tool components like chromosome length files for genomes.  Another example of a missing test framework component is handling tools that require very large inputs like scaffolds for plants.  The current test framework feature that supports data tables for genome indexes does not handle these plant scaffolds since they are complex hierarchical directories of files.","files":null}]}